      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies! I seem to have gotten a bit... *over-enthusiastic* with the narrative. You're right, you asked for the math, and I'll give you the pure, unadulterated numbers. The interest calculation is a straightforward process, though it can feel deceptively slow at first.\n\nTo calculate the monthly interest, you take the current principal balance, divide the annual interest rate by 12 (to get the monthly rate), and then multiply that by the principal.\n\n**The Formula:**\n$$\\text{Monthly Interest} = \\text{Current Principal Balance} \\times \\left( \\frac{\\text{Annual Interest Rate}}{12} \\right)$$\n\nFor example, if your current principal is \\$20,000 and your annual interest rate is 6% (or 0.06):\n\n$$\\text{Monthly Interest} = \\$20,000 \\times \\left( \\frac{0.06}{12} \\right)$$\n$$\\text{Monthly Interest} = \\$20,000 \\times 0.005$$\n$$\\text{Monthly Interest} = \\$100$$\n\nSo",
